## Recursive tree
*a recursive tree is a tree diagram that shows how recursive function calls are made and how they break into smaller subproblems.
*it is in tree like structure.
*it is also called as visualization tree.
it helps us to :
* understand how recursion works
* visualize function calls  in easiest way.
* to calculate time complexity.
example : linear recursion : public class test {
                                static void fun(int n) {
                                    if(n==0) {
                                        return;
                                    }
                                    system.out.println(n);
                                    fun(n-1);
                                   }
                                public static void main(String[] args){
                                   fun(5);
     }
}
call : fun(3) 
*each fun makes one recursive call.
*it is in one straight line tree.
*so it is called linear recursion.
time complexity = O(n)
2.public class test {
      static void fun(int n) {
           if(n==0) {
             return n;
           }
          return fun(n-1) + fun(n-2);
        }
     public static void main(String[] args) {
     system.out.println(fun(5));
  }
}
*Time complexity is O(2^n)
*because it is growing 2^2 so time complexity is 2^n.
important terms in recursion tree:
*root: first function call.
*node: each function call.
*leaf node: base case.
*height: maximum depth of recursion.
*branching factor: number of recursive calls per function.
